If you have a 504/IEP student who has an advocate, don't be snotty to the advocate. Legally, they can (should) have one, and if that person reaches out to you, there's a good reason for that, one you likely don't know.

His getting Covid-19 is karma.

full_text:
Mark Schauer called me later to express his condolences, which was very nice as well as the right thing to do. I was still furious about Walberg and told him about it. He was baffled.

Now, Mark lost that election. Walberg won and won his even more gerrymandered new district.

full_text:
That man politicked at my dad's funeral. Now, if Dad had been there, he would have thrown the guy out. But he wasn't, and I was furious. It wasn't a little rude. 

My brother didn't see it and just thought it nice the jerk came, but I know what I saw and heard.
full_text(utf-8): b"That man politicked at my dad's funeral. Now, if Dad had been there, he would have thrown the guy out. But he wasn't, and I was furious. It wasn't a little rude. \n\nMy brother didn't see it and just thought it nice the jerk came, but I know what I saw and heard."

full_text:
All four of us kids and my stepmom stood in the receiving line afterwards, and when I looked up, there he was, Tim Walberg. My brother didn't see him right away, but I did. 

Then I heard him quietly shake hands around him saying, "I'm Tim Walberg. I'm running for Congress."

full_text:
It devastated us, as you can imagine. My brother handled everything like a pro, funeral stuff to lawyer stuff. I just had to write the obit and give one of the eulogies. I fell apart.

The day of the funeral came, and the church was packed. All these people there to say goodbye.

Anyway, this was back when Mark Schauer was our representative, and Walberg was running against him. Walberg ran a dirty campaign, but I digress.

I volunteered for the Schauer campaign, and my brother donated and hosted a donor party for Walberg. 

Then our dad died.

full_text:
